1
00:00:01,938 --> 00:00:11,928
Tonight's talk is based on the Sutta entitled The Removal of Distracting Thoughts, which, I'm sure you'll agree, sounds like a very attractive proposition.

2
00:00:13,890 --> 00:00:27,522
Last night's Sutta on the different ways of dealing with skilful and unskilful thoughts is particularly suited to practice in everyday life and to wise reflection, where we can examine our thoughts on certain matters.

3
00:00:28,650 --> 00:00:33,576
Tonight's talk relates to distractions that occur during deep meditation.

4
00:00:34,898 --> 00:00:42,926
It offers a broad range of suggestions which include metta, wise reflection, calming and investigation.

5
00:00:44,167 --> 00:00:52,716
It also includes suppression which might be a surprise given the very open-minded non-judgmental stance we associate with Vipassana.

6
00:00:53,878 --> 00:00:56,481
Obviously there is a time for everything.

7
00:00:58,368 --> 00:01:02,652
Here are the Buddha's opening words.

8
00:01:02,671 --> 00:01:10,079
When a bhikkhu is pursuing the higher mind, from time to time he should give attention to five signs.

9
00:01:12,781 --> 00:01:17,066
Note that these instructions are only to be followed from time to time.

10
00:01:18,248 --> 00:01:24,274
Normally we should follow the standard Vipassana instructions we get from the Satipatthana Sutta.

11
00:01:25,503 --> 00:01:30,490
Only from time to time are we to use the alternative discussed tonight.

12
00:01:32,953 --> 00:01:36,579
The Buddha doesn't outline which circumstances warrant the new approach.

13
00:01:37,962 --> 00:01:48,978
While writing this talk, I used this alternative when my mind became too unbalanced for Vipassana and I offer my efforts to follow this teaching as an example.

14
00:01:50,814 --> 00:02:00,947
After a tantalising glimpse of a very still mind that simply knew experience, I made the mistake of thinking, this is the real me.

15
00:02:00,987 --> 00:02:07,676
The Buddhist word for this is vanity, which means that we've succumbed to the delusion of self.

16
00:02:09,138 --> 00:02:14,223
We cling to what we like in our experience, believing this is the real me.

17
00:02:15,520 --> 00:02:25,977
When I fall prey to vanity, I get overly energetic, striving, delighted with my role as the observer who knows experience and investigates the Dhamma.

18
00:02:28,159 --> 00:02:31,284
Ironically, this means that I've lost all objectivity.

19
00:02:32,800 --> 00:02:40,888
Energetically, it felt as though my head was trying to lift off my body, shooting skywards like a rocket towards a very enticing brightness.

20
00:02:41,989 --> 00:02:50,997
I recognised this as vanity, but the attachment was so deep that I couldn't get any objectivity on the experience, and I felt stuck.

21
00:02:53,120 --> 00:02:56,604
This is where the advice given in this Sutta was extremely useful.

22
00:02:57,844 --> 00:03:02,789
Gradually, the skyrocketing, deluded mind was drawn back down to earth.

23
00:03:04,508 --> 00:03:17,860
So in cases where your mind has become focused, but you keep getting stuck in some experience, unable to remain objective, then this may be the right time to try out the instructions from this sutta.

24
00:03:20,860 --> 00:03:28,550
The Buddha then says, when a Bhikkhu is giving attention to some sign, and then goes on to give us advice.

25
00:03:29,953 --> 00:03:33,519
But first, what kind of signs is he talking about?

26
00:03:33,558 --> 00:03:42,512
The Pali word is nimitta, and is used mainly in connection with Samatha meditation, which calms the mind.

27
00:03:44,155 --> 00:03:47,879
The nimitta are signs that we have a good level of concentration.

28
00:03:49,109 --> 00:03:54,735
The mind becomes riveted by present experience and often you notice something unusual.

29
00:03:56,316 --> 00:04:02,502
Though it can appear at any of the sense doors, the most common nimitta are tactile or visual.

30
00:04:03,924 --> 00:04:09,269
You might feel a stream of tingling sensations, for example, or see a pattern of light.

31
00:04:10,729 --> 00:04:17,596
The trouble comes when we become sure there must be some deep message in this strange light or tickling feeling.

32
00:04:18,589 --> 00:04:30,586
Instead of being just another unsatisfactory phenomenon that comes and goes, we start to believe that it signals some exalted state of mind or supreme wisdom that we can achieve.

33
00:04:31,947 --> 00:04:43,803
That was what was happening when my mind got locked into vanity, as described earlier, believing I'd somehow found the real me, the perfect, clear-minded, objective observer.

34
00:04:47,750 --> 00:04:54,300
Before going on to look at the Buddha's advice, I want to draw attention to another phrase in this opening sentence.

35
00:04:56,264 --> 00:05:08,502
When a Bhikkhu is giving attention to some sign, and owing to that sign there arise in him evil, unwholesome thoughts connected with desire, with hate and with delusion.

36
00:05:10,666 --> 00:05:14,533
The sign, remember, signifies a concentrated mind.

37
00:05:14,968 --> 00:05:22,117
So Buddha is saying that evil, unwholesome thoughts can arise because of the sign that we've achieved a concentrated mind.

38
00:05:23,338 --> 00:05:25,161
At first sight this seems weird.

39
00:05:26,242 --> 00:05:31,367
Surely we concentrate our minds as part of the effort to let go of evil, unwholesome thought.

40
00:05:32,309 --> 00:05:36,634
Why on earth undertake a practice that actually causes these to arise?

41
00:05:38,755 --> 00:05:43,221
As our minds become still and focused, underlying troubles show up.

42
00:05:44,483 --> 00:05:52,997
We learn the Dhamma as we navigate through these painful states which get covered over by busyness, sense pleasure and other distractions in daily life.

43
00:05:55,963 --> 00:05:57,786
This is the path of purification.

44
00:05:58,988 --> 00:06:05,259
We easily forget this and believe we're not practicing correctly when negativity shows up while we meditate.

45
00:06:06,286 --> 00:06:13,877
It's comforting to reflect that the Buddha expects such negativity to emerge as a natural consequence of good concentration.

46
00:06:15,098 --> 00:06:18,382
We can take it as a signal that we're moving deeper within.

47
00:06:18,423 --> 00:06:24,391
How are we to work with this deeper layer of negativity?

48
00:06:25,894 --> 00:06:27,636
Let's look at the Buddha's advice.

49
00:06:29,961 --> 00:06:46,958
When a bhikkhu is giving attention to some sign, and owing to that sign there arise in him evil unwholesome thoughts connected with desire, with hate and with delusion, then he should give attention to some other sign connected with what is wholesome.

50
00:06:49,908 --> 00:07:01,358
Normally in Vipassana, when we notice we've been distracted by a thought, we simply note this and center attention on the emotions and feelings associated with that thought.

51
00:07:02,399 --> 00:07:04,242
Our approach is non-judgmental.

52
00:07:04,862 --> 00:07:08,346
It doesn't matter whether the thought is skillful or unskillful.

53
00:07:09,807 --> 00:07:18,295
However, this Sutta offers five alternatives to the standard approach and judgment plays a role right from the start.

54
00:07:19,574 --> 00:07:27,105
In my state of deluded vanity, I was having thoughts like, this is it, I've got it now, oh no, it's gone again.

55
00:07:29,088 --> 00:07:43,050
Although I found it hard to consider these thoughts as evil, because I wasn't actually wishing anyone harm, I knew from long and painful experience how much suffering there is for me in this state of delusion.

56
00:07:44,312 --> 00:07:50,461
I am identifying with a mind state that is experienced as beautiful and trying to hang on to it.

57
00:07:52,245 --> 00:07:57,291
This only brings suffering, deepens delusion, so it is definitely unwholesome.

58
00:07:59,454 --> 00:08:03,081
What are the wholesome signs to which I should attend in these circumstances?

59
00:08:04,403 --> 00:08:14,117
In the commentary on this Sutta by Buddha Gossa, he suggests that metta may be used as the alternative focus when we have been caught by hatred.

60
00:08:14,872 --> 00:08:20,608
while the unattractive aspect of the body is the appropriate focus when we've been caught by lust.

61
00:08:22,291 --> 00:08:31,836
In the case of delusion, which is my concern, he recommends things like living with a teacher, reading Dhamma books, asking questions about the Dhamma.

62
00:08:33,571 --> 00:08:46,403
However, these suggestions don't fit easily into a meditation session, so I used a simple alternative and imagined myself bowing to the Buddha, to Bhante and any teacher who came to mind.

63
00:08:47,765 --> 00:08:52,009
At times, I imagined myself reading a Dhamma book.

64
00:08:52,029 --> 00:09:01,840
All these imaginings had the effect of quelling vanity to some extent, helping me come to terms with the fact that I can't own all the goodness and wisdom in the world.

65
00:09:03,135 --> 00:09:08,982
Do you remember the Suta on the raft and the need to sink the raft once we get to the far shore?

66
00:09:09,003 --> 00:09:12,116
This is basically what I was doing.

67
00:09:13,447 --> 00:09:23,581
The objective observer had become my raft, steadying my mind in Vipassana, helping me through many emotional ups and downs.

68
00:09:25,102 --> 00:09:38,019
Now it was time to let go of that raft, to experience the truth of Anatta at a deeper level, where sensations and feelings are known, but there is no sense of a person watching these.

69
00:09:41,172 --> 00:09:46,578
When I'm going through a bout of vanity, I'm identifying as the person who watches experience.

70
00:09:47,701 --> 00:09:51,765
This showed me my attachment to the fifth canda, consciousness.

71
00:09:53,207 --> 00:09:56,253
I want to be the conscious person that detects experience.

72
00:09:57,673 --> 00:10:00,839
Bowing helps me surrender my hold on consciousness.

73
00:10:01,720 --> 00:10:03,121
Not that I go unconscious.

74
00:10:04,303 --> 00:10:09,070
Sensations and feelings arise, slip by and pass away gracefully.

75
00:10:11,057 --> 00:10:16,946
The body continues to function as normal, but the mind's usual habit of clinging disappears.

76
00:10:17,726 --> 00:10:24,195
And when that goes, I lose the sense of a me who is at the centre of experience, receiving it all.

77
00:10:25,177 --> 00:10:27,219
There are only sensations and feelings.

78
00:10:28,441 --> 00:10:34,688
To my surprise, I find that the absence of central headquarters makes absolutely no difference.

79
00:10:35,309 --> 00:10:38,955
In fact, everything runs much more smoothly.

80
00:10:42,614 --> 00:10:51,025
With each imaginary bow, I got a few seconds where the mind let go of vanity, slipped into the beauty of anatta.

81
00:10:52,467 --> 00:11:06,967
In the Buddha's words, With the abandoning of these thoughts connected to desire, hatred and delusion, his mind becomes steadied internally, quieted, brought to singleness and concentrated.

82
00:11:10,052 --> 00:11:18,446
As an analogy for what we're doing, the Buddha paints the picture of a skilled carpenter knocking out a coarse peg by means of a fine one.

83
00:11:19,889 --> 00:11:23,073
The coarse peg represents our unwholesome thoughts.

84
00:11:24,235 --> 00:11:33,090
To drive these out, we insert the appropriate wholesome thought, which in my case was the thought of bowing to some greater wisdom.

85
00:11:34,927 --> 00:11:48,889
However, after several imaginary bows, my mind refused to cooperate, reattaching itself stubbornly to vanity, determined to experience life within its normal, me-centred map.

86
00:11:50,413 --> 00:11:53,457
So I moved on to the second of the Buddha's suggestions.

87
00:11:55,884 --> 00:12:10,221
If, while he is giving attention to some other sign connected with what is wholesome, there still arise in him thoughts connected with desire, with hate and with delusion, then he should examine the danger in these thoughts thus.

88
00:12:11,443 --> 00:12:16,830
These thoughts are unwholesome, they are reprehensible, they result in suffering.

89
00:12:19,476 --> 00:12:26,011
This is similar to the advice given in last night's Sutta, though the wording here is less nuanced and more severe.

90
00:12:26,052 --> 00:12:31,403
Instead of affliction, we have unwholesome and reprehensible.

91
00:12:32,826 --> 00:12:35,712
Likewise, the analogy he uses is dark.

92
00:12:37,634 --> 00:13:05,447
Just as a man or woman, young, youthful and fond of ornaments, would be horrified, humiliated and disgusted if the carcass of a snake or dog or a human being were hung around his or her neck, so too, when a Biko examines the danger in those thoughts, his mind becomes steadied internally, quieted, brought to singleness and concentrated.

93
00:13:08,076 --> 00:13:16,630
we are to develop horror for unwholesome thoughts of the like we would feel if a rotting carcass were to be slung around our necks.

94
00:13:20,937 --> 00:13:25,625
This is a far cry from the non-judgmental approach we adopt in standard Vipassana.

95
00:13:26,847 --> 00:13:33,038
Obviously there is a time to be open-minded and a time to be judicious and even severe.

96
00:13:34,267 --> 00:13:42,386
In standard Vipassana we maintain objectivity so thoughts of hatred, greed, delusion can do us no harm.

97
00:13:44,003 --> 00:13:52,094
But in the kind of situations the Buddha is addressing here, we're getting caught up in our emotions, no longer objective.

98
00:13:53,655 --> 00:13:56,701
This is when we put our judgmental nature to good use.

99
00:13:57,682 --> 00:14:04,951
We give it full throttle to drive out the desire, hatred and delusion that are showing up as we meditate.

100
00:14:07,134 --> 00:14:11,360
However, this is not an exercise in self-hatred.

101
00:14:12,235 --> 00:14:21,413
What we're condemning are thoughts of greed, hatred and delusion, comparing them to a carcass being hung around our necks.

102
00:14:22,794 --> 00:14:24,658
We're not condemning ourselves.

103
00:14:26,663 --> 00:14:31,071
In fact, we're protecting ourselves against these thoughts.

104
00:14:32,215 --> 00:14:35,018
So it's an exercise in self-care.

105
00:14:35,499 --> 00:14:50,297
When I thought about my delusive thoughts about being the one who knows all, with this image of a carcass hanging around my neck, it brought on shame for the thoughts and a determination not to keep on getting caught up in these.

106
00:14:51,697 --> 00:14:59,707
My attention was still riveted on the bright light and that very still, concentrated mind state that I find so attractive.

107
00:15:00,885 --> 00:15:07,754
But with the image of a carcass around my neck as a protector, the meditation proceeded in a more balanced way.

108
00:15:09,035 --> 00:15:15,183
Whenever desire sprang up, it was quelled by shame as the carcass loomed large in my imagination.

109
00:15:16,285 --> 00:15:18,528
Thus, I could remain objective.

110
00:15:19,909 --> 00:15:27,720
In this precarious balance, I could feel the grief of not being able to fully know and possess that beautiful state.

111
00:15:29,370 --> 00:15:39,705
I could also sense the grief as healing, undermining attachment to the very enticing prospect of being the objective observer of my life.

112
00:15:42,668 --> 00:15:46,614
Thus I could see the wisdom of the Buddha's harsh judgmental words and image.

113
00:15:48,035 --> 00:15:57,589
These are needed to balance the very strong desires, aversions and delusions that emerge when we delve deeply into our experience.

114
00:15:59,121 --> 00:16:10,683
When we can't maintain the balance needed to acknowledge these and let them burn out using the standard approach, we can throw an imaginary carcass around our necks as extra ballast.

115
00:16:14,091 --> 00:16:20,943
But after some time, the image of the carcass began to wane and I felt myself slipping back into vanity.

116
00:16:22,155 --> 00:16:29,903
I then tried the next of the Buddha's suggestions, which is to simply forget the unwholesome thoughts and give them no attention.

117
00:16:31,745 --> 00:16:39,413
He gives the analogy of someone with good eyesight who, not wanting to see a disturbing sight, either shuts his eyes or looks away.

118
00:16:41,375 --> 00:16:49,462
One way we can put this suggestion into practice is by placing attention on calming parts of the body such as the hands and feet.

119
00:16:50,523 --> 00:16:54,375
These don't store emotion in the way that the trunk and face often do.

120
00:16:54,414 --> 00:17:00,955
What we're doing is diverting our attention from whatever is causing disturbance.

121
00:17:03,769 --> 00:17:22,335
In the commentaries, Buddha Gossa suggests placing attention on very mundane things, such as going through the contents of a mending box, picking up the needle and saying, this is the needle, then picking up the thread and saying, this is the thread, and so on.

122
00:17:22,315 --> 00:17:41,032
A variation on this which Bhante suggested to me a few years ago and which is more practical during a meditation session is to open the eyes and deliberately look at objects in the room saying, this is the window, this is the plant, this is the Buddha Rupa and so on.

123
00:17:41,973 --> 00:17:48,660
I keep looking at any one of these for as long as they hold attention, naming them again and again.

124
00:17:51,019 --> 00:18:00,836
It sounds foolish to be staring at objects like this, reminding ourselves what is a plant and what is a window, as if we were in kindergarten.

125
00:18:00,856 --> 00:18:06,987
But the mind can get, in some senses, blown apart when we go deep into experience in Vipassana.

126
00:18:08,650 --> 00:18:16,403
We're learning a completely new way of looking at the world without the delusion of a central control mechanism at its core.

127
00:18:18,086 --> 00:18:27,778
This is deeply disturbing to our psyche and so these very strong urges towards desire, hatred and delusion can be generated as a defense mechanism.

128
00:18:29,221 --> 00:18:33,605
In such a condition we have to take extraordinary care of ourselves.

129
00:18:35,769 --> 00:18:43,638
Recognizing and naming mundane objects is simply another way of caring for and soothing an inflamed mind.

130
00:18:45,458 --> 00:18:56,633
When we're coming to terms with our misunderstanding about the world at its deepest level, it is very comforting to remember that we can still recognize familiar things.

131
00:18:57,372 --> 00:19:00,756
So don't resist the notion of being back in kindergarten.

132
00:19:01,916 --> 00:19:11,367
It's a good place for a confused or overexcited toddler, which is sometimes the level which our minds descend in the challenge of Vipassana.

133
00:19:12,128 --> 00:19:15,232
We've gone through three suggestions so far.

134
00:19:16,094 --> 00:19:25,944
First, we use wholesome thoughts like metta to combat hatred, unattractiveness to combat lust, or bowing as an antidote to delusion.

135
00:19:27,190 --> 00:19:37,262
If that doesn't still the mind, we up the ante by strongly condemning the unwholesome thoughts and conjuring an image of a carcass being slung around our necks.

136
00:19:38,884 --> 00:19:46,355
If the mind is still veering towards desire, hatred or delusion, we try to forget our thoughts by diverting our attention.

137
00:19:48,076 --> 00:19:55,846
This could mean focusing on calming parts of the body or finding external objects at which to look while we name them mentally.

138
00:19:57,008 --> 00:20:01,775
After giving each suggestion, the Buddha then repeats the hoped-for outcome.

139
00:20:02,997 --> 00:20:10,007
His mind becomes steadied internally, quieted, brought to singleness and concentrated.

140
00:20:12,891 --> 00:20:18,598
However, we still have two more options if we're still too unbalanced for vipassana.

141
00:20:19,921 --> 00:20:21,143
The Buddha continues,

142
00:20:23,231 --> 00:20:41,648
If, while he is trying to forget these thoughts and is not giving attention to them, there still arise in him evil, unwholesome thoughts connected with desire, with hate and with delusion, then he should give attention to stilling the thought formation of those thoughts.

143
00:20:43,611 --> 00:20:44,912
He gives this analogy.

144
00:20:47,615 --> 00:20:53,019
Just as a man walking fast might consider, why am I walking fast?

145
00:20:53,506 --> 00:20:54,988
What if I walk slowly?

146
00:20:56,471 --> 00:20:57,732
And he would walk slowly.

147
00:20:57,772 --> 00:21:02,539
Then he might consider, why am I walking slowly?

148
00:21:02,599 --> 00:21:05,203
What if I stand still?

149
00:21:05,263 --> 00:21:08,088
And he would stand still.

150
00:21:09,711 --> 00:21:12,776
Then he might consider, why am I standing?

151
00:21:13,877 --> 00:21:14,798
What if I sit?

152
00:21:16,121 --> 00:21:17,303
And he would sit down.

153
00:21:18,633 --> 00:21:21,715
Then he might consider, why am I sitting?

154
00:21:22,616 --> 00:21:23,738
What if I lie down?

155
00:21:24,878 --> 00:21:26,019
And he would lie down.

156
00:21:29,502 --> 00:21:32,945
Note the phrasing of the first part of the question as why.

157
00:21:32,965 --> 00:21:37,490
In Vipassana, we investigate using what.

158
00:21:38,270 --> 00:21:41,653
For example, what is it that I'm actually experiencing?

159
00:21:43,155 --> 00:21:45,518
What happens if I relax?

160
00:21:45,717 --> 00:21:52,042
We don't ask why, as that gets the mind spinning, trying to think our way out of suffering.

161
00:21:54,003 --> 00:22:00,190
But in this variation of the usual guidance, we are allowing the cognitive mind some room for maneuver.

162
00:22:01,651 --> 00:22:08,797
We're looking for the thought formations, meaning the underlying thought or belief, prompting desire, hatred and delusion.

163
00:22:10,298 --> 00:22:14,442
The Buddha's why question is coupled with the suggestion to relax.

164
00:22:15,518 --> 00:22:17,601
there's an attempt to soothe the mind.

165
00:22:18,682 --> 00:22:23,150
So the why could perhaps be interpreted as, why am I bothering?

166
00:22:25,031 --> 00:22:31,422
Although we're listening to our story, we're also trying to talk ourselves out of the frenzy it is spinning us into.

167
00:22:34,346 --> 00:22:40,715
Buddha Gossa gives another analogy which helps us see how to still our thought formations.

168
00:22:42,349 --> 00:22:49,962
A hare is sleeping beneath a tree when a large piece of fruit falls out of the tree and hits the ground beside his head.

169
00:22:50,837 --> 00:22:57,125
The hare hears the loud thump, feels the vibration and concludes that the earth is being destroyed.

170
00:22:58,047 --> 00:23:00,170
In a blind panic, he starts running.

171
00:23:01,151 --> 00:23:05,797
When other animals see the hare bolting, they also start running away in a panic.

172
00:23:06,817 --> 00:23:18,313
And so the commotion grows until the Bodhisatta, meaning the Buddha in one of his previous lives, this time as a lion, sees all the animals running across the plains.

173
00:23:19,221 --> 00:23:22,866
Instead of joining them he decides to get to the bottom of the matter.

174
00:23:24,128 --> 00:23:27,472
So he asks each of the animals in turn why they are running.

175
00:23:28,575 --> 00:23:38,428
He starts with the largest animal, the elephant, and gradually works his way back to the hare who tells him of the noise and vibration that woke him from sleep.

176
00:23:39,656 --> 00:23:44,103
The lion then asks the hare to take him back to his resting spot under the tree.

177
00:23:45,364 --> 00:23:52,053
The lion sees the piece of fallen fruit and realising that this is what had caused all the commotion.

178
00:23:53,414 --> 00:24:01,125
Thus the Bodhisatta was able to comfort the hare and all the animals and tell them there is nothing to fear.

179
00:24:03,333 --> 00:24:08,300
Both analogies paint a picture of a very patient process.

180
00:24:09,522 --> 00:24:14,430
The lion had to question several animals before he got to the bottom of the hullabaloo.

181
00:24:15,571 --> 00:24:21,580
Similarly, the man described by the Buddha slows himself down in several stages.

182
00:24:23,104 --> 00:24:31,737
So too we need to be very patient with ourselves as we talk ourselves out of whatever rut the mind is steering us into.

183
00:24:35,107 --> 00:24:43,897
My mind can suggest all kinds of reasons why it needs to continue along its dead end, and each one seems like an absolute truth at the time.

184
00:24:45,380 --> 00:24:52,428
When I eventually see through the delusion, it feels like a major breakthrough, and I'll never be the same person again.

185
00:24:52,468 --> 00:24:56,593
But afterwards, I can rarely remember any details.

186
00:24:57,805 --> 00:25:00,086
It's like an argument with our nearest and dearest.

187
00:25:00,708 --> 00:25:05,791
We get stuck fast to our point of view, appalled that they could dare to think otherwise.

188
00:25:06,813 --> 00:25:10,296
But when it's all over, we can hardly remember what the row was about.

189
00:25:13,239 --> 00:25:18,263
I persuaded myself to relax for long enough to get my mind around the Buddha's advice.

190
00:25:20,204 --> 00:25:21,807
What emerged was the question.

191
00:25:23,628 --> 00:25:24,950
Why try to grasp?

192
00:25:26,270 --> 00:25:27,491
Why not let go

193
00:25:30,796 --> 00:25:35,563
This quieted my mind for a while as it contemplated the suggestion.

194
00:25:36,984 --> 00:25:39,008
But then an underlying fear showed up.

195
00:25:40,670 --> 00:25:46,778
I discovered I was very afraid of what would become of me if I lost that lofty glimpse of purity.

196
00:25:49,281 --> 00:25:52,886
Having acknowledged this, another question was framed.

197
00:25:54,369 --> 00:25:55,431
Why be afraid?

198
00:25:56,792 --> 00:25:58,255
Why not trust?

199
00:25:59,804 --> 00:26:04,169
Again, the mind relaxed, considering the suggestion.

200
00:26:06,372 --> 00:26:10,016
This had the effect of bringing me more in contact with the fear.

201
00:26:11,998 --> 00:26:24,833
As my body sensed all the unpleasant sensations, my mind saw a horrid image of myself as completely worthless, the polar opposite of the ideal state I had been trying to catch hold of.

202
00:26:26,382 --> 00:26:37,539
Although I was 90% identified with this state of worthlessness, I was just about able to remember that this was a trance-free experience, not my real self.

203
00:26:40,644 --> 00:26:48,297
When I could relax to the degree needed to frame another question, what emerged was a reiteration of the previous one.

204
00:26:49,578 --> 00:26:50,580
Why be afraid?

205
00:26:51,602 --> 00:26:52,743
Why not trust?

206
00:26:54,563 --> 00:27:05,561
After a few moments' consideration, the mind relaxed more deeply into the unwanted state and shame became the predominant emotion.

207
00:27:08,346 --> 00:27:17,803
Acknowledging shame brought a degree of relief and with that I could also sense the caring nature of the investigating strand in my mind.

208
00:27:20,112 --> 00:27:24,176
After a while it felt okay to ask, why be ashamed?

209
00:27:25,278 --> 00:27:26,378
Why not let it go?

210
00:27:26,398 --> 00:27:34,729
After some time pondering this, my mind confessed the kernel of its fear.

211
00:27:36,530 --> 00:27:39,314
Because I don't know what will happen next.

212
00:27:41,276 --> 00:27:46,962
This, I believe, was the thought formation at the basis of all the commotion.

213
00:27:49,896 --> 00:27:56,326
This is a big dilemma for ourself, that delusion of being a separate unit from the rest of the world.

214
00:27:57,588 --> 00:28:02,415
It needs to be in control, to be able to predict what's coming down the line.

215
00:28:02,435 --> 00:28:08,444
It's the foreman in the factory, the headmaster in the school.

216
00:28:08,424 --> 00:28:12,428
As far as the boss is concerned, he or she is running the show.

217
00:28:14,069 --> 00:28:17,251
But in this situation, the boss is in a fix.

218
00:28:17,271 --> 00:28:23,297
All the conveyor belts have jammed, the workers are threatening to walk out, the pupils are causing a riot.

219
00:28:24,438 --> 00:28:29,261
The situation has got totally out of control and the boss hasn't a clue what to do.

220
00:28:31,865 --> 00:28:38,230
Through practising with this, I've learned that I can happily embrace the don't-know state.

221
00:28:39,137 --> 00:28:44,042
In fact, it can be a great joy because it relieves responsibility.

222
00:28:44,963 --> 00:28:50,809
I can step down from my role as the boss, join the rebellious workers in riotous freedom.

223
00:28:51,951 --> 00:28:56,355
Though in practice, the riot stops the instant the boss steps down.

224
00:28:57,978 --> 00:29:02,563
Everything changes once I stop pretending to be in control.

225
00:29:05,210 --> 00:29:13,582
Though these memories help, I still get stuck to the pedestal, fooled into believing that everything will disintegrate if I don't maintain order.

226
00:29:15,244 --> 00:29:22,675
Getting through that barrier of fear, climbing down from the boss's pedestal, this requires lots of patience.

227
00:29:24,057 --> 00:29:33,731
As best I can, I bear witness to the fear, feeling its texture in my body, trusting that things will somehow work out.

228
00:29:35,769 --> 00:29:41,236
Eventually, I slipped off the pedestal into a joyful freedom from responsibility.

229
00:29:41,256 --> 00:29:47,143
I could also sense the danger of identifying with that carefree state.

230
00:29:48,124 --> 00:29:50,426
But of course, this is just another dead end.

231
00:29:50,467 --> 00:30:00,157
Identifying with any state of mind, even the most joyous, brings suffering when the state breaks up as it's bound to do eventually.

232
00:30:02,247 --> 00:30:11,540
Knowing this, I made an effort to tread the middle path between carefree joy and the attempt to identify as the boss and control matters.

233
00:30:13,684 --> 00:30:16,628
The desire to plunge into identification was very strong.

234
00:30:17,971 --> 00:30:23,519
I really wanted to define myself either as the one who is joyful or the control freak.

235
00:30:24,741 --> 00:30:30,651
Either identification felt preferable, more stable than the precarious middle ground.

236
00:30:31,913 --> 00:30:36,338
I no longer had the balance of mind needed to frame any questions for inquiry.

237
00:30:37,441 --> 00:30:43,288
So at that stage I moved on to the last of the Buddha's suggestions for dealing with distractions.

238
00:30:46,513 --> 00:30:52,021
Before going on to that I want to emphasize how gentle we need to be with our questions.

239
00:30:53,263 --> 00:31:00,974
The process is like psychotherapy where the therapist needs to be very respectful of the client and not rush them along.

240
00:31:02,321 --> 00:31:05,505
The therapist strand in my mind needs constant restraining.

241
00:31:06,526 --> 00:31:08,948
The client needs a lot of reassurance.

242
00:31:10,709 --> 00:31:17,734
Using Buddha Gossa's analogy, the lion needs to be reminded not to eat the animals he is questioning.

243
00:31:18,836 --> 00:31:22,398
And they need a lot of reassurance that his motives are benign.

244
00:31:24,320 --> 00:31:31,906
This is especially as important as the lion approaches the smaller animals and as we go deeper into our fears.

245
00:31:33,253 --> 00:31:39,423
The hare, in Buddha Gossa's story, at first refuses to take the lion to his resting place.

246
00:31:40,865 --> 00:31:48,256
The lion slowly talks him into this disclosure, speaking sometimes gently, sometimes firmly.

247
00:31:49,857 --> 00:32:00,173
And when the lion works out the cause of the problem, he doesn't crow in triumph, but takes time to reassure the animals that there's nothing to fear.

248
00:32:02,026 --> 00:32:12,545
This paints a picture of the tenderness and respect with which we care for the fearful strand in our minds as we try to get to the bottom of the disturbance.

249
00:32:15,790 --> 00:32:17,875
Going on to the final suggestion.

250
00:32:19,458 --> 00:32:46,765
If, while he is giving attention to stilling the thought formations, there still arise in him evil, unwholesome thoughts, connected with desire, with hate and with delusion, then, with teeth clenched and his tongue pressed against the roof of his mouth, he should beat down, constrain and crush mind with mind.

251
00:32:49,916 --> 00:32:56,766
By comparison to the gentle language of the previous example, he uses very forceful words here.

252
00:32:58,106 --> 00:33:09,461
He gives an equally stark analogy of a strong man seizing a weaker man by the head or shoulders and beating him down, constraining him and crushing him.

253
00:33:11,550 --> 00:33:13,273
What are we to make of this?

254
00:33:13,314 --> 00:33:20,945
Elsewhere in the scriptures, the Buddha praises qualities like patience, care, kindness.

255
00:33:22,588 --> 00:33:26,976
But here he is asking us to beat someone up, at least in our imagination.

256
00:33:28,557 --> 00:33:31,182
It would appear that there is a time for everything.

257
00:33:32,324 --> 00:33:37,271
And this is the time for our aggressive tendencies to be put to good use.

258
00:33:39,344 --> 00:33:54,086
In my case, then, as I attempted to find a middle way between heedless irresponsibility and absolute control, I used suppression as a means of forcing myself back towards the middle ground.

259
00:33:56,108 --> 00:34:01,876
At times, I felt the strong urge towards that sense of absolute control, becoming the boss.

260
00:34:03,078 --> 00:34:07,224
To combat this, I put all my energy into saying, ''No.''

261
00:34:08,605 --> 00:34:13,094
Very strong tensions ran through the body to combat desire in this way.

262
00:34:14,097 --> 00:34:17,023
My jaw set like iron, my breath stopped.

263
00:34:18,005 --> 00:34:24,318
Body and mind were completely locked in combat between I want and no.

264
00:34:26,340 --> 00:34:38,460
Eventually, a truce was called, the breath started flowing, the tension eased up a little, and I felt a trickle of energy flowing through the most jammed up section of the body.

265
00:34:40,324 --> 00:34:51,623
The ending of the battle didn't feel like victory or defeat, more like moving on, with the sense of something within having been freed up, although I couldn't name what had changed.

266
00:34:52,867 --> 00:35:01,217
the sensations that flowed through the previously jammed up area released a trickle of joy and even bliss in their wake.

267
00:35:03,219 --> 00:35:17,998
But after a few moments the desire to identify locked hard onto some new outlet, at times the trickle of joy, at other times the grief at not being able to control this and call it mine.

268
00:35:19,260 --> 00:35:25,947
Again my body and mind stiffened as I resisted this new identity with all my might.

269
00:35:28,809 --> 00:35:38,599
On and on it went until desire burnt out somewhat and I could feel myself relaxing, no longer overwhelmed by the need to identify with experience.

270
00:35:40,842 --> 00:35:49,150
At that point I returned to the standard Vipassana technique, knowing experience objectively without interfering.

271
00:35:50,985 --> 00:35:56,996
Although I was feeling battle-weary, I sensed that some deeper wisdom had been gained.

272
00:35:58,978 --> 00:36:07,532
I found myself reflecting on the meaning of Anatta and saying, So I really am not this body and mind.

273
00:36:09,735 --> 00:36:18,309
Although there was still some fear and grief at the words, these emotions were balanced by acceptance and wonder.

274
00:36:19,791 --> 00:36:28,523
The obvious next question, what on earth am I then, was not forming, which was a blessed relief.

275
00:36:30,304 --> 00:36:35,231
There was a degree of ease with being unable to understand the mystery of what I am.

276
00:36:35,271 --> 00:36:44,802
The phrase, peace beyond understanding, came to mind and started to make sense.

277
00:36:46,369 --> 00:36:55,219
At some level I'd broken free from the tyrant within me who demands to know and understand what life is all about.

278
00:36:56,820 --> 00:37:02,387
Though I knew this was just a temporary break, I was deeply grateful for the relief.

279
00:37:05,911 --> 00:37:15,920
To close the Sutta, the Buddha repeats his five suggestions for dealing with distractions which come up when we get deeply concentrated.

280
00:37:17,335 --> 00:37:23,865
First, we give attention to the alternative wholesome thought, such as metta, for example.

281
00:37:25,489 --> 00:37:43,039
If that doesn't work, we reflect on the danger posed by the unwholesome thoughts, which is basically the same as in last night's sutta, though in this case the language is more strongly condemnatory, and we sling a carcass around our necks to drive the point home.

282
00:37:44,960 --> 00:37:55,554
Thirdly, we forget about the disturbing thoughts, distract our attention elsewhere, such as to the periphery of the body or objects in the room.

283
00:37:57,376 --> 00:38:05,588
Fourthly, we head the process of inquiring into the underlying thought formations with the aim of bringing them to stillness.

284
00:38:07,490 --> 00:38:13,599
Finally, there is the advice to suppress the disturbance by force majeure.

285
00:38:15,418 --> 00:38:19,907
After each suggestion, the Buddha reiterates the hoped for outcome.

286
00:38:22,411 --> 00:38:33,951
With the abandoning of the unwholesome thoughts, the mind becomes steadied internally, quieted, brought to singleness and concentrated.

287
00:38:36,327 --> 00:38:39,871
Note that there is no judgment if any of these steps fail.

288
00:38:39,931 --> 00:38:48,360
We don't have to think of ourselves as a bad meditator if we have to go to the last step and suppress the disturbance.

289
00:38:49,902 --> 00:38:54,788
Instead we can think of this as a step of deep purification.

290
00:38:57,431 --> 00:39:03,938
The Buddha concludes by saying that using this practice the meditator becomes a master of thought.

291
00:39:05,572 --> 00:39:12,717
he will think whatever thought he wishes to think and he will not think any thought he does not wish to think.

292
00:39:15,920 --> 00:39:19,664
Wouldn't it be wonderful never to think thoughts we don't want to think?

293
00:39:20,644 --> 00:39:23,706
Never again to worry or obsess over details?

294
00:39:24,927 --> 00:39:27,449
Never to harbour resentment or jealousy?

295
00:39:28,690 --> 00:39:30,672
Never to think ourselves into a panic?

296
00:39:31,733 --> 00:39:35,476
And imagine always being able to think those thoughts we want to think

297
00:39:36,722 --> 00:39:51,929
Always able to think well of ourselves and others, to wish ourselves well in all circumstances, to find some positive, optimistic thought, even when we feel depressed or when the situation seems desperate.

298
00:39:56,197 --> 00:40:11,083
Even if bandits were sawing us apart limb by limb, as the Buddha describes in another sutta, we could think compassionately of our poor body and of the bandits who are making such bad karma for themselves.

299
00:40:13,661 --> 00:40:33,797
The Buddha's final words on the matter are that having become a master of thought the meditator has severed craving flung off the fetters and with the complete penetration of conceit he has made an end to suffering.

